"Meteorological datasets: The most relevant items are Dataset 3 Wetterdaten - täglich (MD1) Dresden-Klotzsche, which provides daily signals (Tagesmittel der Temperatur, Tagesmittel der Relativen Feuchte, Tagesmittel des Luftdrucks, Niederschlag, Sonnenscheindauer) suitable for tracking grass color changes at high temporal resolution, and Dataset 1 Wetterdaten (Jahreszahlen), which offers annual Lufttemperatur, Sonnenscheindauer und Niederschläge for long-term context (roughly 2000–2024). Soil moisture: No suitable soil-moisture dataset is included in the five datasets; to interpret soil-moisture–driven color shifts you would need ESA CCI Soil Moisture or a Saxony-specific soil-moisture source beyond these. Saxony/Chemnitz context: Dataset 2 Baeume (Chemnitz) provides spatial tree data (e.g., properties.BAUMART, BAUMNUMMER, PFLANZDATUM) that can inform shading and microclimate adjustments but does not supply climate/soil-moisture data. Data quality and limits: note nulls (Dataset 1 has 350 nulls in merkmal_4; Dataset 2 has 174 nulls in PFLANZDATUM; Dataset 5 has 299 nulls in merkmal_3), and the meteorological data come from Dresden (MD1) and Leipzig (Jahreszahlen) rather than Chemnitz, so cross-city comparability requires careful spatial adjustment. Actionable takeaway for Chemnitz grass-color interpretation: rely on the daily meteorology from Dataset 3 for event-level analyses and on the annual context from Dataset 1, supplement shading/microclimate considerations with Dataset 2 when modeling grass color, and explicitly address the soil-moisture gap by integrating an external soil-moisture dataset (e.g., ESA CCI Soil Moisture) to avoid misattributing color signals to weather alone."